=== ABSTRACT (REVISED) ===
\begin{abstract}
Large language models (LLMs) are increasingly used as scoring and
representation engines for recommendation, yet comparisons across LLM-based
recommenders are often confounded by different candidate sets, backbones,
importers, and evaluation schemas. We first contribute a rigorous unified
same-candidate reranking protocol: every method ranks the same 101 candidates
(one positive and 100 popularity-sampled negatives) for each of 10{,}000 users,
uses the same Qwen3-8B backbone when an LLM is required, and is evaluated with a
shared importer, identical metrics, exact coverage checks, and paired
Holm-corrected bootstrap tests, with full provenance. Against eight
official-code-level LLM-based recommendation baselines across eight Amazon
domains (Beauty, Books, Electronics, Movies, Sports, Toys, Home, Tools), our
central empirical finding is that a \emph{task-grounded pointwise LLM relevance
posterior} -- the model's own per-candidate relevance probability, used directly
as the ranking score -- ranks first in six of the eight domains, improving
NDCG@10 by $+21.6\%$ to $+53.2\%$ over the strongest baseline (leading on all
seven metrics HR@5/@10/@20, NDCG@5/@10/@20, MRR in five of these six domains ---
Electronics, Sports, Toys, Home, Tools; 56/56 paired-significant --- and on six
of seven on Books, HR@20 versus LLMEmb the exception). In the remaining two
domains it is not first: rank~2 on Beauty ($-11\%$ NDCG@10 behind ProEx, though
this shortfall is not Holm-significant on any metric, leaving \method{}
statistically indistinguishable from the strongest baseline) and mid-pack at
rank~5 on Movies ($-24\%$ behind LLMEmb, substantially behind the stronger
baselines). We report these two losses explicitly rather than
dropping them. We compute paired Holm-corrected bootstrap tests on all eight
domains: on the six winning domains \method{} is significantly ahead on all 56
metric/baseline pairs (54/56 on Books), while on Movies it is significantly
behind the stronger baselines on 22 of 56 pairs. To test whether this ranking
advantage survives frozen-model substitution, we re-run the identical pipeline
under two additional different-family LLMs (Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct and
Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3) across all eight domains: across the six winning
domains, $17$ of $18$ backbone$\,\times\,$domain cells clear the strongest
official baseline (Mistral first in all six, Llama in five; Llama-Books a $1.0\%$
near-miss vs.\ LLMEmb), at a $\sim 10$--$25\%$ lower absolute level consistent
with backbone capability; on Beauty and Movies the loss direction also transfers
to both additional backbones.

We then report a rigorous \emph{negative result} on the design space this work
set out to study. We instrument the pointwise posterior with a principled
calibrated-uncertainty and risk-adjusted ranking family that decomposes
uncertainty into boundary ambiguity, a calibration gap, evidence support, and
counterevidence. Under a leave-one-component-out ablation and a
raw-probability attribution, this machinery does not improve same-candidate
ranking: the zero-risk setting is test-best in all four diagnostic domains, a
confidence-only variant matches or exceeds the full family in three of those
four domains, and individual uncertainty terms are inert or mildly harmful. The
working ranking signal lies in the posterior itself, not in the
uncertainty decomposition. As a minor, descriptive observation -- and one we
caveat as partly circular -- the event-level uncertainty signal does stratify
reliability, but we do not claim it improves ranking. This is a scoped result
about same-candidate reranking, not a full-catalog recommender SOTA claim.
\end{abstract}

=== CONCLUSION (REVISED) ===
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We set out to study whether a task-grounded uncertainty framework can improve
LLM-based reranking under a controlled same-candidate protocol, and our main
contribution is the protocol itself: every method ranks the same 101 candidates
per event for 10{,}000 users, with a shared Qwen3-8B backbone, a shared
importer, identical metrics, exact coverage checks, and paired Holm-corrected
bootstrap tests. Under this protocol, our central finding is that a
task-grounded pointwise LLM relevance posterior---the model's own per-candidate
relevance probability used directly as the ranking score---ranks first against
eight official-code-level baselines in six of the eight Amazon domains we tested
(Books, Electronics, Sports, Toys, Home, Tools), improving NDCG@10 by $+21.6\%$
to $+53.2\%$ over the strongest baseline and leading on all seven HR/NDCG/MRR
metrics in five of those six domains (Electronics, Sports, Toys, Home, Tools) and
on six of seven on Books (HR@20 versus LLMEmb the exception). In the other two
domains it is not first---rank~2 on Beauty ($-11\%$ NDCG@10, though its shortfall
versus ProEx is not Holm-significant on any metric) and mid-pack at rank~5 on
Movies ($-24\%$, substantially behind the four stronger baselines)---which we
report rather than omit. We compute paired Holm-corrected bootstrap tests on all
eight domains: on the six winning domains \method{} is significantly ahead on all
56 metric/baseline pairs (54/56 on Books), while on Movies it is significantly
behind the stronger baselines on 22 of 56 pairs and on Beauty none of the losses
to ProEx is Holm-significant. This is a scoped same-candidate reranking claim, not
a full-catalog recommender SOTA result. The ranking advantage survives
frozen-model substitution: re-running the identical C-CRP scoring pipeline under
two additional different-family LLMs (Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct and
Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3) over all eight domains clears the strongest official
baseline in $17$ of $18$ backbone$\,\times\,$winning-domain cells (Mistral first
in all six, Llama in five, with Llama-Books a $1.0\%$ near-miss), with the
official baselines held at their unified-Qwen comparison values; the absolute
level is consistent with backbone capability (\S\ref{sec:second_backbone}).

The diagnostic modules locate this signal precisely and yield a rigorous
negative result. Leave-one-component-out ablations and a raw-probability
attribution show that the uncertainty decomposition and the risk-adjusted
ranking family do not improve same-candidate ranking over the posterior they are
built on: the test-best risk exponent is zero in all four domains, a
confidence-only variant matches or exceeds the full configuration, and the
individual uncertainty terms are inert or mildly harmful. The working ranking
signal lies in the pointwise posterior itself, not in the uncertainty machinery.
The event-level uncertainty signal does stratify ranking reliability, but we
report this only as a caveated, partly mechanical descriptor, not as evidence
that uncertainty improves ranking. We present the calibrated-uncertainty and
risk-adjusted family as an analyzed and characterized design space, and leave
its use as a reliability descriptor or for downstream abstention to future work.

=== LIMITATIONS (Limitations subsection in analysis.tex) ===
\subsection{Limitations}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{No full-catalog claim.} We evaluate controlled reranking over
    101 candidates per user. Candidate generation and full-catalog retrieval
    remain future work.
    \item \textbf{Two additional backbones tested; broader model coverage open.}
    The formal main comparison uses a unified Qwen3-8B backbone across all eight
    Amazon-domain same-candidate tasks (with the uncertainty diagnostics run on
    four of them). To test whether the same-candidate ranking advantage survives
    frozen-model substitution, we re-ran the identical C-CRP scoring pipeline
    under two additional different-family LLMs --- Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct and
    Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 --- across all eight domains
    (\S\ref{sec:second_backbone}): the headline NDCG@10 rank-first result clears
    the strongest official baseline in $17$ of $18$
    backbone$\,\times\,$(winning-domain) cells (Mistral in all six, Llama in five;
    Llama-Books a $1.0\%$ near-miss vs.\ LLMEmb), with the official baselines held
    at their unified-Qwen comparison values; the absolute level is consistent with
    backbone capability ($\sim 10$--$25\%$ lower). The Beauty/Movies losing
    direction also transfers to both additional backbones. This establishes
    cross-family transfer of the win/loss partition under frozen-model
    substitution; we have not tuned baselines per-backbone (a re-tuned
    cross-backbone SOTA comparison is left to future work), and other LLMs,
    catalogs, or retriever distributions may still change calibration and
    uncertainty behavior.
    \item \textbf{Descriptive uncertainty diagnostics.} The observation module
    shows that uncertainty stratifies reliability, but it is not a causal
    intervention. It does not prove that changing uncertainty alone would change
    ranking utility.
    \item \textbf{Uncertainty decomposition is inert for ranking.} The
    leave-one-component-out diagnostics and the raw-probability attribution show
    that the calibrated-uncertainty and risk-adjusted terms do not improve
    same-candidate ranking over the pointwise posterior they are built on; the
    test-best risk exponent is zero in all four domains. The paper therefore
    claims that a task-grounded pointwise relevance posterior ranks first under
    the controlled same-candidate protocol, and reports the uncertainty
    decomposition as a characterized negative result plus a descriptive
    reliability signal---not as a validated ranking-improvement mechanism.
    \item \textbf{External adapter policy.}\label{lim:backbone} We preserve
    official-code-level
    baseline mechanisms and use a shared Qwen3-8B representation bridge for
    same-candidate scoring. This gives a fair controlled comparison, but it is
    not the same claim as reproducing each method under its original full-catalog
    serving stack. A bridge-fidelity check (\S\ref{sec:results}) finds the
    Qwen3-8B bridge recovers $\approx\!90\%$ of LLM2Rec's native same-candidate
    NDCG@10 (Tools $110\%$, Sports $78\%$), so the bridge does not collapse
    baselines to the floor; we have not, however, run a native-backbone
    reproduction for every baseline.

